    <h2>Lecture 9: Solving Partial Differential Equations</h2>
    <hr>
    <h3>Solving PDEs by Direct Integration</h3>
    <p>For some simple PDEs, a solution can be found by integrating the equation directly. When integrating with respect to one variable, the "constant" of integration is an arbitrary function of the other variable(s).</p>
    
    <details>
        <summary>Example: Solve $$\frac{\partial^2 z}{\partial x^2} = xy^2$$</summary>
        <div class="solution">
            <p><strong>1. First Integration:</strong></p>
            <p>Integrate with respect to $$x$$, treating $$y$$ as a constant.</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} = \int xy^2 dx = \frac{x^2}{2}y^2 + f(y)$$
            </div>
            <p>Here, $$f(y)$$ is an arbitrary function of $$y$$ that acts as the constant of integration.</p>
            
            <p><strong>2. Second Integration:</strong></p>
            <p>Integrate again with respect to $$x$$.</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$z = \int \left(\frac{x^2}{2}y^2 + f(y)\right) dx = \frac{x^3}{6}y^2 + x f(y) + g(y)$$
            </div>
            <p>Here, $$g(y)$$ is another arbitrary function of $$y$$, representing the new constant of integration.</p>
        </div>
    </details>
    
    <hr>
    <h3>First-Order Quasi-linear PDEs: Lagrange's Method</h3>
    <p>A first-order quasi-linear PDE has the general form:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$P(x,y,z)\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} + Q(x,y,z)\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} = R(x,y,z)$$
    </div>
    <p>This type of equation is solved using Lagrange's method of auxiliary equations. The auxiliary equations are:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\frac{dx}{P} = \frac{dy}{Q} = \frac{dz}{R}$$
    </div>
    <p>By solving this system, we find two independent solutions, $$u_1(x,y,z) = c_1$$ and $$u_2(x,y,z) = c_2$$. The general solution is then an arbitrary function relating these two solutions, often written as $$F(u_1, u_2) = 0$$.</p>
    
    <details>
        <summary>Example: Solve $$x\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} + y\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} = 3z$$</summary>
        <div class="solution">
            <p><strong>1. Set up Auxiliary Equations:</strong></p>
            <p>Here, $$P=x, Q=y, R=3z$$. The equations are:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{dx}{x} = \frac{dy}{y} = \frac{dz}{3z}$$
            </div>
            <p><strong>2. Find the First Solution ($$u_1$$):</strong></p>
            <p>Take the first two fractions and integrate:</p>
            <p>$$\int\frac{dx}{x} = \int\frac{dy}{y} \implies \ln(x) = \ln(y) + \ln(c_1) \implies u_1 = \frac{x}{y} = c_1$$</p>
            
            <p><strong>3. Find the Second Solution ($$u_2$$):</strong></p>
            <p>Take the second and third fractions and integrate:</p>
            <p>$$\int\frac{dy}{y} = \int\frac{dz}{3z} \implies \ln(y) = \frac{1}{3}\ln(z) + \ln(c_2) \implies 3\ln(y) = \ln(z) + \ln(c_2^3) \implies u_2 = \frac{y^3}{z} = c_2'$$</p>
            
            <p><strong>4. Write the General Solution:</strong></p>
            <p>The general solution is an arbitrary function of $$u_1$$ and $$u_2$$.</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$F\left(\frac{x}{y}, \frac{y^3}{z}\right) = 0$$
            </div>
        </div>
    </details>
    
    <hr>
    <h3>Lagrange's Method of Multipliers</h3>
    <p>When the variables in the auxiliary equations cannot be easily separated, we can use the method of multipliers. For any multipliers $$l, m, n$$, the following relation holds:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
        $$\frac{dx}{P} = \frac{dy}{Q} = \frac{dz}{R} = \frac{l\;dx + m\;dy + n\;dz}{lP + mQ + nR}$$
    </div>
    <p>The strategy is to choose multipliers $$l, m, n$$ such that the denominator becomes zero: $$lP + mQ + nR = 0$$. If the denominator is zero, the numerator must also be zero, which gives us a new integrable equation: $$l\;dx + m\;dy + n\;dz = 0$$.</p>
    
