    <h3>Second-Order Linear PDEs</h3>
    <h4>Classification</h4>
    <p>A general second-order linear PDE in two variables has the form:</p>
    <div class="math-display">
         $$A\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2} + B\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x \partial y} + C\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2} + D\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} + E\frac{\partial u}{\partial y} + Fu = G(x,y)$$
    </div>
    <p>The equation is classified based on the value of the discriminant $$B^2 - 4AC$$:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>If $$B^2 - 4AC > 0$$, the PDE is <strong>Hyperbolic</strong> (e.g., wave equation).</li>
        <li>If $$B^2 - 4AC = 0$$, the PDE is <strong>Parabolic</strong> (e.g., heat equation).</li>
        <li>If $$B^2 - 4AC < 0$$, the PDE is <strong>Elliptic</strong> (e.g., Laplace's equation).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h4>Method of Separation of Variables</h4>
    <p>This method is used to solve homogeneous linear PDEs. It works by assuming the solution can be expressed as a product of functions, each depending on only one of the independent variables. For a function $$z(x,y)$$, we assume a solution of the form $$z(x,y) = X(x)Y(y)$$.</p>

    <details>
        <summary>Example: Solve $$\frac{\partial^2 z}{\partial x^2} + 4\frac{\partial^2 z}{\partial y^2} = 0$$</summary>
        <div class="solution">
            <p><strong>1. Classify the PDE:</strong></p>
            <p>Here, $$A=1, B=0, C=4$$. The discriminant is $$B^2-4AC = 0 - 4(1)(4) = -16 < 0$$, so the equation is <strong>elliptic</strong>.</p>

            <p><strong>2. Assume and Substitute the Solution:</strong></p>
            <p>Assume $$z(x,y) = X(x)Y(y)$$. Substituting into the PDE gives:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$X''(x)Y(y) + 4X(x)Y''(y) = 0$$
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>3. Separate the Variables:</strong></p>
            <p>Rearrange the equation to separate the functions of $$x$$ and $$y$$:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{X''}{X} = -4\frac{Y''}{Y}$$
            </div>
            <p>Since the left side depends only on $$x$$ and the right side only on $$y$$, both must be equal to a constant, say $$k$$.</p>
            
            <p><strong>4. Solve the ODEs:</strong></p>
            <p>This gives us two ordinary differential equations:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>$$\frac{X''}{X} = k \implies X'' - kX = 0$$. The solution is $$X(x) = a_1e^{\sqrt{k}x} + a_2e^{-\sqrt{k}x}$$.</li>
                <li>$$-4\frac{Y''}{Y} = k \implies 4Y'' + kY = 0$$. The solution is $$Y(y) = b_1\cos\left(\frac{\sqrt{k}}{2}y\right) + b_2\sin\left(\frac{\sqrt{k}}{2}y\right)$$.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>5. Form the General Solution:</strong></p>
            <p>The complete solution is the product $$z(x,y) = X(x)Y(y)$$. More general solutions are formed by taking a superposition (sum) of these solutions for different values of k. The specific values for the constants are found using initial or boundary conditions.</p>
        </div>
    </details>
